<TITLE> Eid prayer timings </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 27 (bdnews24.com)Muslims in Bangladesh are preparing to celebrate on Saturday the Eid-ul-Azha, their second largest religious festival. The main Eid congregations or Jamaats will be held in the National Eidgah ground adjacent to the High Court. Deputy director of Islamic Foundation ATM Inamul Haque told bdnews24.com that the main Eid jamaat will begin at 9:00am. Chief Imam of Gulshan central mosque Maolana Shamsul Haque will lead the prayers, said Haque. Khatib of National mosque Mohammad Salahuddin, who leads the prayers, is now in Saudi Arabia to perform Hajj. President Rahman, cabinet members, senior judges, bureaucrats, politicians and people from all walks of society will take part in it. Special arrangements have been made for women to take part in the Eid prayers. Space has been allocated for the wives of the envoys of foreign missions and diplomats. Dhaka City Corporation has arranged for water supply and mobile toilets. It has arranged for 360 Eid prayer congregations in the city's 90 wards. A separate congregation will be held at the playground of Dhaka University, taking to 361 the total number in the city, a press statement said. There will be another Jamaat at 9:00am in the south plaza of parliament building, organised by the parliament secretariat. Baitul Mukarram National Mosque will hold five congregations, with the first taking place at 8:00am, the second at 9:00am, the third at 10:00am, the fourth at 11:00am and the final one at 11:45am. At the Banani Darbar Sharif of Biswa Jaker Manjil, Eid prayers will start at 7:00am, with a second jamaat at 8:00am, third at 9:00am, fourth at 10:00am and the last will be held at 11:00am. Dhaka University's Central Mosque will host two Eid prayers. The first will start at 8:30am while the second will be at 9:30am. Two separate congregations will also be held on the lawns of Salimullah Hall and Shahidulah Hall at 8:30am and 9:00am respectively. bdnew
